    readTime: '10 min',
    excerpt: 'Content optimized for AI search looks different from content optimized for traditional search. Here\'s what to change.',
    content: `<p>Content optimization for AI search engines is a genuinely different discipline from traditional SEO content optimization. The fundamental difference is the audience: traditional SEO content is written to be clicked on and read by a human; AI search content is written to be parsed, extracted, and synthesised by an AI system before a human ever sees it. Understanding this distinction is the starting point for effective AI search optimization.</p>
<h2>The Question-Answer Format</h2>
<p>AI search tools are most commonly used for question-answering. Users ask conversational questions - "what is the best marketing agency for e-commerce brands in Toronto?" - and expect synthesised answers. Content that is structured to answer specific questions directly, with clear and factual responses, is more likely to be incorporated into AI-generated answers than content that communicates the same information in a promotional or narrative format.</p>
<p>This means structuring your content around the specific questions your customers ask AI tools. Use question-format headings, provide direct and specific answers, and include the kind of factual, verifiable information (statistics, specific examples, named case studies) that gives AI tools the confidence to cite your content as a source.</p>
<h2>Structured Data and Schema Markup</h2>
<p>Schema markup helps AI systems understand what your content is about, who it's from, and how it relates to other entities on the web. For businesses, this means using Organization schema, LocalBusiness schema (for location-based businesses), FAQPage schema for question-answering content, and Article schema for blog content. Well-implemented schema is a direct signal to AI systems about how to interpret and cite your content.</p>
<h2>Entity Signals and Consistency</h2>
<p>AI language models build representations of entities - brands, people, places, concepts - from the information available about them across the web. Inconsistent information creates uncertainty in these representations, which reduces the probability of confident citation. Auditing and ensuring consistency in how your brand is described across your website, social profiles, directories, and press mentions is a foundational AI optimization step.</p>
<h2>Content Freshness and Specificity</h2>
<p>Real-time AI search tools like Perplexity weight recent, specific content more heavily than older, generic content. A blog post published last month with specific, current information will outperform a pillar page published two years ago with evergreen information. Building a consistent content publishing schedule that produces specific, current, and well-structured content is both a traditional SEO best practice and an AI search optimisation strategy.</p>`,
